Ok I'm curious, how did you make the craters and the texture? I could really use some advice to improve my crappy little planet

It's actually not as advanced as it might look. I was quite surprised by the result myself.

The diffuse map is really rather ugly - just a mess of blurry colours. Most of the model's appearance comes from a displacement map that I applied to an ordinary sphere (it's also pretty ugly on its own).

I simply used the cloud and noise filters in Photoshop to give the sphere a generally rough appearance, and then I just kept adding more or less dark, blurred circles (sometimes with brighter edges) to give it craters and other surface features. It's quite a demanding (not to mention tedious) process. Had to restart 3DS Max several times.

Heres a render I made a while ago. Didn't do much work on the jetpack, that was just an idea that ran in my head at the last moment and I made it in like a minute.

If we're just posting any old thing I guess I can show the things I used to do before I started doing this stuff for a living. Hover over the gear icon in the top right of the imgur frame and view them in full resolution if you want to be able to see everything.

Javascript is disabled. View full album

1. This one I made during my late college years. It was a 3 day project for a class I can't quite remember anymore. It's one of the only things from college that I did that I still have.

2. This one came a couple of years later, after the 2nd Transformers movie came out. I didn't feel I had the patience to do a full model of Bumblebee, so I made a low-res version. It got popular enough that it received a daily devation on DeviantArt.

3. I made this one after the Bumblebee. While I didn't feel like I could do a hi-res version of Bumblebee, I still wanted to do the car. Tis a sexy car, and I believe I got the perfect angle to show off its curves.

4. Ok, well I caved and started building the hi-res version. This was Bumblebee's foot, or rather the first iteration of it. It was very choppy work, and I went back and redid most of the pieces.

5. Remember how I said I redid most of the pieces? Well now you can see. I'm pretty sure I changed every piece on the feet(around 50 objects per foot, if memory serves), and it looked a lot nicer, and a lot more like the movie version.

6. A few days after the previous picture I took these, showing off the progress I was making on the legs. I made some minor changes to the feet, too.

7. This, unfortunately, was the last update. I had gotten a job in my field and wasn't able to continue. Sadly I lost the project files, and haven't really had the desire to go back to it. The final part count(per leg/foot) was over 100. Polycount was nearing the 100k range(per leg/foot), and it looks a bit like a vacuum cleaner from those views. Still, I'm proud of what I was able to accomplish before I quit.

Those were really the last things that I did outside of a few things for KSP, which are visible on the forums anyway. Most of my time is spent doing things that I can't share.
